        <div>
            <pb facs="#TL-0552.jpg" n="part4_p078.jpg" xml:id="img_0078" corresp="https://id.acdh.oeaw.ac.at/tillich-lectures/part4_p078.jpg"/>
            
            <p facs="#facs_78_tr_3">
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_1" n="N001"/>décrire
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_2" n="N002"/>-547.
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_3" n="N003"/>LECTURE XLII, April 17, 956
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_4" n="N004"/>QN: Are there any inmutable principles which should always government man’s action in society,
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_5" n="N005"/>or are there just artificial rules of repression created by the will of the times? Do you accept
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_6" n="N006"/>any of the concepts of natural law advanced by political powers-or something like that?
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_7" n="N007"/>You gaveimpressions of the sex drive, one example of the repressions resulting from artificia¬
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_8" n="N008"/>divine or national laws. Please give additional exemples.
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_9" n="N009"/>PT: Now who has asked this question? Would you be so good to formula it in one or two words?
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_10" n="N010"/>QN: There are two questions. The first is: do you accept any of the natural-law concepts advanced
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_11" n="N011"/>by temnal theorists? You seem to suggest that any of these ideas of an inmutable, eternal,
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_12" n="N012"/>moral order existing outside of man are ;mainly artificiaiicreations of the individual times.
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_3_tl_13" n="N013"/>These merely repress man’svaives.
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_78_tr_1">
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_1" n="N001"/>discussed,
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_2" n="N002"/>PT: Yes, now let’s first stick to this question. You ask me something which I
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_3" n="N003"/>not last hour, but the week before, and I don't know whether you attended when I gave thisächeme:
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_4" n="N004"/>love as the ultimate principle, which is universal and by natural law, because it belong to the nature
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_5" n="N005"/>of man. Then this third level, the concrete situation, of kthical decision, here and now, in this
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_6" n="N006"/>irrespectable unique situation, which happens in this moment. Then between this, the formation
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_7" n="N007"/>of rules and laws which are on the one hand hanging on the ultimate principle, and on the other
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_8" n="N008"/>hand are gained by experiences on the basis of the concrete situation in thenelopment of mankind.
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_1_tl_9" n="N009"/>We called this the middle axioms, or the rules of wisdom. The first was love; the third was the
            </p>
            <p facs="#facs_78_tr_2">
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_1" n="N001"/>kairos, the unique moment in time; and the middle was wisdom. And the wisdom is the unity of
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_2" n="N002"/>something immovable—which we defined as love—and on the other hand, the always changing elements
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_3" n="N003"/>of the concrete situation. So my theory of the natural law is not identical with that of the Roman
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_4" n="N004"/>Catholic Church, where special definite contents are identified with the eternal natural law—that's
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_5" n="N005"/>dans un
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_6" n="N006"/>Monsieur Mʼadresse de
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_7" n="N007"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_8" n="N008"/>Mais Mlle Dʼœur de lʼhonneur et très obéissant serviteur
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_9" n="N009"/>que je suis avez
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_10" n="N010"/>Monsieur
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_11" n="N011"/>Monsieur, de
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_12" n="N012"/>dʼune manière beaucoup dʼordre les
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_13" n="N013"/>dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_14" n="N014"/>dʼavoir lʼautre beaucoup dʼune manière
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_15" n="N015"/>déciter
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_16" n="N016"/>Monsieur M r de
               <lb facs="#facs_78_tr_2_tl_17" n="N017"/>dʼun autre
            </p>
            
